sentences: Carrie Belle (Wilson) Adams (1859–1940) was the first American woman to conduct a public performance of Handel's oratorio, "Messiah."
Formative years ==
Born in Oxford, Ohio on July 28, 1858 (alternate birth date June 29, 1859), Carrie Belle Wilson was the oldest child of Allie (Myers) Wilson and David Wilson, a songwriter and music educator.
Born in Oxford, Ohio on July 28, 1858 (alternate birth date June 29, 1859), Carrie Belle Wilson was the oldest child of Allie (Myers) Wilson and David Wilson, a songwriter and music educator.
As the American Civil War was waged across a major portion of the United States during the early 1860s, Carrie Wilson was studying music with her father.
A child prodigy, she sang for a convention of musicians in Millville, Ohio, when she was just seven years old.
According to biographer Jacob Henry Hull, she was also "a brilliant pianist and accompanist from her girlhood days.
"In 1872, she and her parents and five siblings moved to Paris, Illinois, where her father founded the Paris Musical Institute.
Three years later, at the age of 16, she published an anthem – the first of many compositions she would pen over the years.

By 1876, she was serving as the organist and choir director for the Paris Presbyterian Church.
On July 21, 1880, Carrie Belle Wilson married amateur playwright Allyn G. Adams.

sentences: Suffering from a heart condition, Carrie Belle (Wilson) Adams was admitted to a private hospital in Portland, Oregon, for treatment sometime in late November or early December 1940.
Suffering from a heart condition, Carrie Belle (Wilson) Adams was admitted to a private hospital in Portland, Oregon, for treatment sometime in late November or early December 1940.
She remained there for several weeks until her death on December 15, 1940.
She remained there for several weeks until her death on December 15, 1940.

According to a statement made to The Oregonian by a representative of her longtime publisher, Lorenz Publishing Co., "Adams' compositions [were being performed] each Sunday by an average of 300,000 choir singers" at the time of her death.
Dr. Raymond B. Walker, the pastor of Portland's First Congregational Church officiated at her funeral services, which were held at J. P. Finley & Son on December 18, 1940.
